'''Peter Boizot''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]] (born 1928) is an [[entrepreneur]], [[restaurateur]] and [[art]] [[collecting|collector]] and [[Philanthropy|philanthropist]], renown as the founder of [[PizzaExpress]].

[[File:Peter_Boizot_Outside_PizzaExpress.jpg|thumb|alt=Peter Boizot outisde PizzaExpress.|Peter Boizot outside one of the first ''[[PizzaExpress]]'' restaurants.]]

==Early Years==
Boizot was born, educated and currently lives in [[Peterborough]], [[United Kingdom]].
He was educated at [[The_King's_School,_Peterborough|King<U+2019>s School]], Peterborough and later became head boy.<ref>[http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/peter_boizot_happy_birthday_mr_peterborough_1_142913 Peter Boizot Happy Birthday Mr Peterborough] The Independent, 16 November 2009</ref> 
He vowed, in his childhood, to never to eat meat when witnessing the slaughter of an animal.<ref>[http://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/mr-pizza-and-all-that-jazz-profile-peter-boizot-1285293.html Mr Pizza And All That Jazz] The Independent, 26 January 1997</ref> He remained a [[vegetarian]] ever since.

===Education===
Boizot attended King<U+2019>s School in Peterborough where he was head boy.<ref>[http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/lifestyle/the-guide/arts-culture/peterborough_icon_peter_boizot_to_auction_off_artwork_1_3140592 Peterborough Icon Peter Boizot To Auction Off Artwork] Peterborough Today, 2011</ref>
In 1953, Boizot earned an Honours Degree in History at [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge]].
Boizot received an [[Honorary Degree]] at [[Loughborough University]] in 2000 in recognition for his successful business acumen and career, and for his contributions to [[Peterborough]].<ref>[http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/et-business/business-news/peter_boizot_at_77_no_plans_to_sit_back_and_relax_just_yet_1_69179 No Plans To Sit Back And Relax Just Yet] Peterborough Today, 16 November 2006</ref>

===PizzaExpress===
Boizot founded [[PizzaExpress]] in 1965, after travelling through [[Europe]] and noticing that he was unable to eat an authentic [[pizza]] slice in [[London]].<ref>[http://www.pizzaexpress.com/our-restaurants/about-pizza-express.aspx PizzaExpress] PizzaExpress, 2012</ref> 
Boizot floated [[PizzaExpress]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]] in 1993.<ref>[http://www.thisismoney.co.uk/money/markets/article-1712492/Pizza-Express-holds-out-for-second-listing.html PizzaExpress Holds Out For Second Listing] This Is Money, 13 February 2011</ref>
His first restaurant opened in [[Soho]], London, to much acclaim with a second PizzaExpress opening in 1967. It grew quickly because of its authentic [[Italy|Italian]] taste and unique [[art|artistic]] approach.<ref>[http://www.peach-report.com/Latest/686503/pizzaexpress_founder_peter_boizot_an_industry_icon.html PizzaExpress founder Peter Boizot an Industry Icon ] Peach Report, 19 November 2010</ref>
Whilst having sold his share of PizzaExpress, Boizot continues to be involved in the business, where he is currently holds position of President.

===Charity===
In 1977, Boizot created the Veneziana pizza in his PizzaExpress restaurant to gain attention to and raise funds for [[Venice in Peril]]. 5p from each Veneziana pizza sold would be donated to the charity, a charity set up to raise funds to restore and conserve works of art and architecture in Venice. This charity initiative still exists at all PizzaExpress restaurants, but the amount donated has increased to 25p from each pizza. Boizot<U+2019>s efforts have raised over <U+00A3>2,000,000 to date.<ref>[http://www.pwwsolicitors.co.uk/charitable-applications/charity-details/the-veneziana-fund The Veneziana Fund ] Pothecary Witham Weld Solicitors, 2011</ref> From his Venice in Peril charity efforts, Boizot was awarded a [[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic]] in 1996 for his devotion/services to the State of Italy.[http://www.debretts.co.uk/people/biographies/browse/b/10167/Peter%20James+BOIZOT.aspx Peter Boizot ] Debretts, 2012</ref>

==Peterborough==
Boizot is locally renowned as <U+2018>Mr Peterborough<U+2019> because of the work and funds that he has put back into his hometown of [[Peterborough]]. He purchased and then modernised his favourite local haunt, the Great Northern Hotel in 1993.<ref>[http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/news/environment/peter_boizot_happy_birthday_mr_peterborough_1_142913 Peter Boizot: Happy birthday, Mr Peterborough ] Peterborough Today, 16 November 2009</ref> In 1997 he bought the ailing Peterborough Football Club and invested <U+00A3>5 million into its resurrection. Boizot acquired the Odeon cinema in 1996 and transformed it into a multi-purpose entertainment venue complete with a theatre/concert room and conference room.<ref>[http://www.peterboroughhiddenheritage.org/heritage/Odeon.html Odeon Cinema ] Peterborough Hidden Heritage, 2008</ref>

==Jazz==
Boizot is an avid jazz fan. He opened his first jazz club, the PizzaExpress Jazz Club in London<U+2019>s Soho district in 1969, whilst founding the Soho Jazz Festival several years later.* He then opened another two PizzaExpress Jazz Club<U+2019>s across the UK. These jazz clubs have played host to greats such as Ella Fitzgerald, Sting, Norah Jones and Jamie Cullum.<ref>[http://www.jazzwisemagazine.com/jazz-gig-guide/venueevents/2 Jazz Gig Guide ] Jazzwise Magazine, 2011</ref>

==Art==
Boizot began collecting [[art]] from an early age and has incorporated art into many of his ventures. At [[PizzaExpress]] and the jazz clubs he commissioned pop artists such as [[Peter Blake]], Eduardo Paolozzi and [[Enzo Apicella]] to fill the walls of the establishments.
In 2011, Boizot sold the majority of his art collection near his hometown of Peterborough.<ref>[http://www.peterboroughtoday.co.uk/lifestyle/the-guide/arts-culture/peterborough_icon_peter_boizot_to_auction_off_artwork_1_3140592 Peterborough icon Peter Boizot to auction off artwork ] Peterborough Today, 12 October 2011</ref> He worked with [[Enzo Apicella]], a well-known restaurant designer, who has been credited with being the visual architect of PizzaExpress.

